<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="212" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1425,2012]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1425,1450]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Ocellar setae mostly extremely minute in male (
<figureCitation box="[857,928,1425,1450]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1437,1459]" captionTargetBox="[162,1425,561,1406]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[150,1436,559,1416]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Leucophenga argentata de Meijere, 1914, male head and terminalia in lateral view. A. Head, proclinate orbital setae (Orb 3), anterior reclinate orbital setae (Orb 2), posterior reclinate (Orb 1), ocellar setae (oc s) and postocellar setae (poc s); B. Epandrium (epand), surstylus (sur) and cercus (cerc); C. Hypandrium (hypd), paramere (pm), gonopods (gon) and aedeagus (aed); D. Paramere; E. Aedeagus and thin process (tp). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264554/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
A), but normal in female; postocellar setae extremely minute (
<figureCitation box="[369,439,1461,1486]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1437,1459]" captionTargetBox="[162,1425,561,1406]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[150,1436,559,1416]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Leucophenga argentata de Meijere, 1914, male head and terminalia in lateral view. A. Head, proclinate orbital setae (Orb 3), anterior reclinate orbital setae (Orb 2), posterior reclinate (Orb 1), ocellar setae (oc s) and postocellar setae (poc s); B. Epandrium (epand), surstylus (sur) and cercus (cerc); C. Hypandrium (hypd), paramere (pm), gonopods (gon) and aedeagus (aed); D. Paramere; E. Aedeagus and thin process (tp). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264554/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
A); Orb3 (proclinate orbital setae) and Orb2 (anterior reclinate orbital setae) very close together (
<figureCitation box="[259,328,1500,1525]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1437,1459]" captionTargetBox="[162,1425,561,1406]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[150,1436,559,1416]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Leucophenga argentata de Meijere, 1914, male head and terminalia in lateral view. A. Head, proclinate orbital setae (Orb 3), anterior reclinate orbital setae (Orb 2), posterior reclinate (Orb 1), ocellar setae (oc s) and postocellar setae (poc s); B. Epandrium (epand), surstylus (sur) and cercus (cerc); C. Hypandrium (hypd), paramere (pm), gonopods (gon) and aedeagus (aed); D. Paramere; E. Aedeagus and thin process (tp). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264554/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
A); wing hyaline, lacking any pattern on membrane, brown on R1 medially (
<figureCitation box="[1195,1264,1500,1525]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1705,1727]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,679,1663]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,679,1664]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Wing of male: A. Leucophenga argentata; B. L. bicuspidata sp. nov.; C. L. fuscivena sp. nov.; D. L. longipenis sp. nov.; E. L. quadricuspidata sp. nov.; F. L. tricuspidata sp. nov. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264550/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); halter mostly yellowish, with a black patch at knob (
<figureCitation box="[589,669,1540,1565]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[335,1247,195,1936]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[335,1248,195,1937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dorsal and lateral view of thorax: A, B. Leucophenga argentata in male; C, D. L. argentata in female; E, F. L. bicuspidata sp. nov. in male; G, H. L. bicuspidata sp. nov. in female; I, J. L. fuscivena sp. nov. in male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264551/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[681,698,1541,1565]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[337,1250,193,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[337,1251,193,1935]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dorsal and lateral view of thorax: A, B. Leucophenga fuscivena sp. nov. in female; C, D. L. longipenis sp. nov. in male; E, F. L. longipenis sp. nov. in female; G, H. L. quadricuspidata sp. nov. in male; I, J. L. tricuspidata sp. nov. in male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264552/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">4</figureCitation>
); aedeagus slender, laterally with thin process(es) (tp in 
<figureCitation box="[1335,1412,1540,1565]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1437,1459]" captionTargetBox="[162,1425,561,1406]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[150,1436,559,1416]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Leucophenga argentata de Meijere, 1914, male head and terminalia in lateral view. A. Head, proclinate orbital setae (Orb 3), anterior reclinate orbital setae (Orb 2), posterior reclinate (Orb 1), ocellar setae (oc s) and postocellar setae (poc s); B. Epandrium (epand), surstylus (sur) and cercus (cerc); C. Hypandrium (hypd), paramere (pm), gonopods (gon) and aedeagus (aed); D. Paramere; E. Aedeagus and thin process (tp). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264554/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
E, 8D, 9D, 11D) and/or acute process(es) (ap in 
<figureCitation box="[660,779,1576,1601]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 7" captionStart-1="FIGURE 8" captionStart-2="FIGURE 9" captionStart-3="FIGURE 10" captionStart-4="FIGURE 11" captionStartId-0="11.[151,250,1887,1909]" captionStartId-1="13.[151,250,1421,1443]" captionStartId-2="14.[151,250,1329,1351]" captionStartId-3="15.[151,250,1954,1976]" captionStartId-4="17.[151,250,1833,1855]" captionTargetBox-0="[161,1432,960,1859]" captionTargetBox-1="[162,1426,504,1389]" captionTargetBox-2="[161,1425,360,1294]" captionTargetBox-3="[164,1426,991,1919]" captionTargetBox-4="[156,1427,770,1797]" captionTargetId-0="figure@11.[151,1436,948,1866]" captionTargetId-1="figure@13.[151,1436,487,1400]" captionTargetId-2="figure@14.[151,1436,343,1308]" captionTargetId-3="figure@15.[151,1436,983,1932]" captionTargetId-4="figure@17.[151,1436,759,1811]" captionTargetPageId-0="11" captionTargetPageId-1="13" captionTargetPageId-2="14" captionTargetPageId-3="15" captionTargetPageId-4="17" captionText-0="FIGURE 7. Leucophenga bicuspidata sp. nov., male terminalia in lateral view. A. Epandrium, surstylus and cercus; B. Hypandrium, paramere, gonopods and aedeagus; C. Paramere; D. Aedeagus and acute processes (ap). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." captionText-1="FIGURE 8. Leucophenga fuscivena sp. nov., male terminalia in lateral view. A. Epandrium, surstylus and cercus; B. Hypandrium, paramere, gonopods and aedeagus; C. Paramere; D. Aedeagus, thin process (tp) and acute process (ap). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." captionText-2="FIGURE 9. Leucophenga longipenis sp. nov., male terminalia in lateral view. A. Epandrium, surstylus and cercus; B. Hypandrium, paramere, gonopods and aedeagus; C. Paramere; D. Aedeagus, acute process (ap) and thin process (tp). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." captionText-3="FIGURE 10. Leucophenga quadricuspidata sp. nov., male terminalia in lateral view. A. Epandrium, surstylus and cercus; B. Hypandrium, paramere, gonopods and aedeagus; C. Paramere; D. Aedeagus and acute processes (ap). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." captionText-4="FIGURE 11. Leucophenga tricuspidata sp. nov., male terminalia in lateral view. A. Epandrium, surstylus and cercus; B. Hypandrium, paramere, gonopods and aedeagus; C. Paramere; D. Aedeagus, acute processes (ap) and thin process (tp). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/264555/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/264556/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/264557/files/figure.png" httpUri-3="https://zenodo.org/record/264558/files/figure.png" httpUri-4="https://zenodo.org/record/264559/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">Figs. 7â11</figureCitation>
D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="213" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1425,2012]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1437,151,612]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="213" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,1612,1637]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">Description.</emphasis>
Male and female: Eyes red to brownish red. Ocellar triangle brownish to brown. Frons narrow, nearly parallel, slightly silvery pollinose, with a few minute setulae medially. All orbital setae large; Orb3 and Orb2 separated by distance less than 1/5 of that between Orb2 and Orb1 (posterior reclinate) (
<figureCitation box="[1128,1196,1687,1712]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1437,1459]" captionTargetBox="[162,1425,561,1406]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[150,1436,559,1416]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Leucophenga argentata de Meijere, 1914, male head and terminalia in lateral view. A. Head, proclinate orbital setae (Orb 3), anterior reclinate orbital setae (Orb 2), posterior reclinate (Orb 1), ocellar setae (oc s) and postocellar setae (poc s); B. Epandrium (epand), surstylus (sur) and cercus (cerc); C. Hypandrium (hypd), paramere (pm), gonopods (gon) and aedeagus (aed); D. Paramere; E. Aedeagus and thin process (tp). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264554/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
A); Orb2 placed afore Orb 
<quantity box="[194,234,1727,1756]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
some specimens. Arista plumose. Face usually yellowish in male, yellow to brownish in female; facial carina absent. Palpus usually brownish yellow to brownish, slightly more enlarged distally in female than in male. Vibrissa prominent; subvibrissal setae small. Gena and postgena narrow. Mesonotum usually yellowish in male, yellow to brownish in female. Postpronotal lobe usually yellowish to yellow, with 1â3 long seta(e) and a few of shorter setae. Acrostichal setulae in ca. 6â10 irregular rows. Prescutellar setae large. Pleura lacking any stripe above. Katepisternum yellow to yellowish, with two long and some small setae. Meron yellowish to yellow. Scutellum usually yellowish to yellow at tip. Subscutellum swollen. Basal medial-cubital crossvein absent. Costal vein between R2+3 and R4+5 distally with ca. 4â8 peg-like spinules on ventral surface; R2+3 slightly curved; R4+5 and M1 nearly parallel distally. Legs yellowish, except for the brown on knees of mid and hindlegs. Thorax entirely with dense silvery pollinosity. Abdominal tergites usually yellowish in male, yellow in female, with dense silvery pollinosity mainly before 4th tergite, and with dark color patches obviously variable between male and female (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1795,1817]" captionTargetBox="[164,1418,211,1752]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,193,1773]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Abdominal tergites patterns: A â D. Leucophenga argentata; E, F. L. bicuspidata sp. nov.; G â I. L. fuscivena sp. nov.; J â L. L. longipenis sp. nov.; M. L. quadricuspidata sp. nov.; N. L. tricuspidata sp. nov.; O. Color legend." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264553/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="213">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Male terminalia: Epandrium desclerotized, pubescent, usually with several setae around ventral corner to posterior margin and undeveloped apodeme along anterior margin. Surstylus usually broad and flat, nearly entirely pubescent, with several setae on outer and inner surfaces. Cercus separated from epandrium, pubescent and setigerous. Hypandrium (gonopod in 
<bibRefCitation author="Bachli" box="[569,769,371,396]" pageId="6" pageNumber="213" refString="Bachli, G., Vilela, C. R., Escher, S. A. &amp; Saura, A. (2004) The Drosophilidae (Diptera) of Fennoscandia and Denmark. Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica, Volume 39. Brill, Leiden, New York, 362 pp." type="book" year="2004">
BÃ¤chli 
<emphasis box="[649,698,371,395]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="213">et al</emphasis>
. 2004
</bibRefCitation>
) anteriorly fused to aedeagal apodeme, laterally broadened, lacking any seta. Gonopods (dorsal arch in 
<bibRefCitation author="Bachli" box="[650,857,407,432]" pageId="6" pageNumber="213" refString="Bachli, G., Vilela, C. R., Escher, S. A. &amp; Saura, A. (2004) The Drosophilidae (Diptera) of Fennoscandia and Denmark. Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica, Volume 39. Brill, Leiden, New York, 362 pp." type="book" year="2004">
BÃ¤chli 
<emphasis box="[732,790,407,431]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="213">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
) fused with each other, forming slightly triangular plate, anteroventrally with curved, median rod. Paramere (outer paraphysis in 
<bibRefCitation author="Bachli" box="[1021,1221,443,468]" pageId="6" pageNumber="213" refString="Bachli, G., Vilela, C. R., Escher, S. A. &amp; Saura, A. (2004) The Drosophilidae (Diptera) of Fennoscandia and Denmark. Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica, Volume 39. Brill, Leiden, New York, 362 pp." type="book" year="2004">
BÃ¤chli 
<emphasis box="[1100,1149,443,467]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="213">et al</emphasis>
. 2004
</bibRefCitation>
) contiguous to arm of aedeagal apodeme basally, glabrous, usually with a few sensilla distally. Aedeagal basal bridges (inner paraphysis in 
<bibRefCitation author="Bachli" box="[306,507,515,540]" pageId="6" pageNumber="213" refString="Bachli, G., Vilela, C. R., Escher, S. A. &amp; Saura, A. (2004) The Drosophilidae (Diptera) of Fennoscandia and Denmark. Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica, Volume 39. Brill, Leiden, New York, 362 pp." type="book" year="2004">
BÃ¤chli 
<emphasis box="[386,434,515,539]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="213">et al</emphasis>
. 2004
</bibRefCitation>
) contiguous to median rod of gonopods, bifurcated basomedially.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,612]" pageId="6" pageNumber="213">In the following descriptions of individual species, only characters showing interspecific variability are described for brevity.</paragraph>
